<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Tax Reform Proposal Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Coalition Considers Compromise </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302094994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0939 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- Compromise proposals were 
presented on Thursday [3 February] at a meeting of leaders of 
the seven coalition parties over a new tax plan proposed by 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa to break a deadlock resulting 
from opposition by the largest party in the government, 
coalition sources said. 
  The proposals include nullifying the rate of 7 percent set 
by 
Hosokawa for the tax to be imposed on sales of most goods and 
services, they said. 
  Instead, the Hosokawa administration should set up a 
consultative body to enable the coalition partners to debate a 
new rate for the tax, the sources said. 
  The compromise calls for part of the revenues from the new 
tax to be put into a special account, instead of the general 
account, they said. 
  The new proposals emerged after the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [of Japan -- SDPJ] threatened to withdraw its six 
ministers from the cabinet unless the coalition upheld the 
demand to legislate a provision that would funnel all the 
revenue from the new tax to finance welfare policy measures. 
  Hosokawa had earlier rejected the SDP's demand to insert 
into 
the new tax legislation wording that would obligate the 
government to spend all the revenue form the tax on welfare. 
  On Wednesday, the SDP responded sharply to Hosokawa's plan 
to 
replace the current 3 percent consumption tax with the "national 
welfare tax." 
  Prior to the meeting, SDP Secretary General Wataru Kubo and 
his Democratic Socialist Party Counterpart Takashi Yonezawa 
agreed that it is the best way to nullify the new 7 percent tax, 
coalition officials said. Yonezawa conveyed the accord to 
Hosokawa by telephone and urged renewed talks on the tax. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

