<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Tax Reform Proposal Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Coalition Fails To Reach Accord </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302154594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1522 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 4 KYODO -- The ruling coalition parties 
failed to narrow their differences Thursday over a new indirect 
tax plan proposed by Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
decided to resume discussions on the issue Friday morning. 
  Representatives from the seven coalition parties held tough 
negotiations throughout the day. 
  A compromise emerged during the talks that revenues from the 
"national welfare tax" proposed by Hosokawa be solely spent to 
finance welfare-related expenditures and the rate for the new 
tax be discussed by parties at a consultative body, coalition 
sources said. 
  However, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) [SDPJ], which 
threatened to withdraw its six ministers from the cabinet unless 
its demands for amendments to the new tax are met, urged that 
discussions on the issue last two years, while the government 
insisted on one year, the sources said. 
  The Finance Ministry stuck to its demand that the rate for 
the tax be specified in a tax bill, they said. 
  Hosokawa announced early Thursday morning the creation of 
the 
7 percent "national welfare tax" on goods and services, to be 
introduced in April 1997, to finance 6 trillion yen in proposed 
tax cuts in place of the current 3 percent consumption tax. 

</TEXT>

