<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Tax Reform Proposal Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Effect on Economic Package Viewed </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302084594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0837 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302084594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura indicated Thursday [3 February] the 
government may not announce the long-awaited economic relief 
package within the day as planned. Takemura told a press 
conference, "it may be difficult for the government to decide on 
the contents of the package by the end of the day." 
  The ruling coalition is split over whether or not to 
introduce a new national welfare tax to finance the planned tax 
reduction, the focus of the economic pump-primer reportedly 
worth 15 trillion yen, the largest ever. 
  The Social Democratic Party (SDP), the largest force in the 
coalition, is dead-set against the proposal and has threatened 
to withdraw its officials from the cabinet if the government 
pushes ahead with the plan. 
  Takemura also said the Democratic Socialist Party, another 
component of the coalition, urged Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa to give up the new tax idea and give further debate to 
the issue on how to offset the tax cut. 
  A government source said Hosokawa is unlikely to rethink his 
decision on the proposal. "The prime minister is determined. I 
don't think he will change his mind," said the source. 

</TEXT>

