<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Strength Decreases With Departure of Two </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302115094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1141 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- The Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [of Japan -- SDPJ] said Thursday [3 February] it has 
notified the Secretariat of the House of Councillors of the 
departure of two nonparty members of its parliamentary group. 
  The defection of the two, Hideo Den and Masao Kunihiro, who 
voted against the SDP when an upper house plenary session 
approved the government's package of political reform bills on 
Saturday, reduces the parliamentary group's membership from 73 
to 71. 
  The party has yet to decide how to deal with a group of 
other 
SDP members who rebelled against SDP policy during the vote and 
opposed the package. 
  Also on Thursday, former Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) 
upper 
house member Chinpei Nozue, now an independent, joined another 
parliamentary group composed of governing coalition members of 
the Japan New Party, Shinseito, and the Reform Coalition Party, 
increasing the group's membership from 26 to 27. 
  Nozue's defection leaves the LDP with 95 members in the 
upper 
house. 

</TEXT>

