<H3> <TI>   Rice Farmers Aid Totals Record 440 Billion Yen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202132194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1242 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Payments by the 
government-backed mutual aid funds to farmers to compensate for 
damage by natural disasters hit a record 439.42 billion yen last 
year due to the extremely poor rice harvest, government 
officials said Wednesday [2 February]. The previous record was 
248.39 billion yen in 1980, the officials at the Agriculture, 
Forestry and Fisheries Ministry said. 
  Under the mutual aid system, farmers pay premiums to a 
governmental agricultural insurance body and in case of disaster 
receive insurance money depending on the extent of the damage 
suffered. 
  In 1993, Japan's rice crops were the poorest in the postwar 
period, with the rice crop index remaining at 74, meaning 
extremely poor. The unseasonably cool, wet summer damaged the 
growth of rice plants across the nation. 
  The officials said the ministry has so far paid the money to 
1,366,000 farmers, about half the contracted farmers. Per 
capita payments averaged 321,600 yen, they said. 
  Damage was most severe in Hokkaido, Miyagi and Aomori 
Prefectures, they added. 
  For the payments, the ministry used part of revenue it 
gained 
from sales of imported rice, the officials said. The government 
made a profit by selling imported rice, which is far cheaper 
than the sum the government pays domestic producers, at the 
government sale price for domestic rice to protect Japanese 
farmers. 

</TEXT>

