<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Market Price of Domestic Rice `Rising' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202123794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1140 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Prices for domestically 
produced rice are rising sharply in jiyu-mai dealings, or a grey 
market outside government channels, due to growing speculation 
that consumers would prefer to buy domestic rice even at higher 
prices, industry sources said Wednesday [2 February]. 
  Also contributing to the uptrend of rice prices is the fact 
that the pace of importing rice from such countries as China and 
Australia has been slower than initially expected, causing 
concern about the amount of rice available, they said. Rice 
dealers want to build up their stocks of domestic rice 
regardless of the rising prices, they added. 
  In Japan, the government buys about 20 percent of the rice 
crop and oversees the independent distribution of a further 40 
percent. 
  There is also a grey market supported by rice growers and 
distributors outside the government's control. 
  According to the sources, prices for popular domestic rice 
brands on the black market have shot up since the previous week 
by an average of 1,000 yen or more for 60 kilograms. 
  Koshihikari rice, a product of Niigata Prefecture and one of 
the most popular brands, is now sold for about 41,000 yen per 
bag. Akita Komachi of Akita Prefecture is 38,000 yen and 
Sasanishiki of Miyagi Prefecture is 36,000 yen. 
  The inflation in the grey market will inevitably affect 
retail prices of rice, they said. 
  A supermarket in Tokyo's Setagaya Ward is selling 
Koshihikari 
for 11,900 yen per 10 kilograms. 
  "It is selling all right at the price. I suppose consumers 
do not mind paying a little more for tasty rice," a clerk at the 
supermarket said. 

</TEXT>

