<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Retail Market Plans for Imported Rice Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202091294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Japanese rice wholesalers 
will start delivering imported rice to retailers in 
mid-February, mostly without blending the imports with domestic 
rice, industry sources said Wednesday [2 February]. Japan is 
expected to import as much as two million tons of rice, 
including supplies from the United States and Thailand, to make 
up for a shortage resulting from the worst postwar harvest in 
1993. 
  A major rice wholesaler in Yokohama said Thai rice will be 
sold at 300 to 320 yen per kilogram, about half the price of 
domestic rice. Californian rice will sell for about 408 yen per 
kilogram. 
  The government is expected to start delivering Californian 
rice to wholesalers around February 10. 
  Yamatane Corp., a leading rice wholesaler, said it will sell 
imported rice without blending it with domestic rice, giving 
consumers a chance to taste a variety of rice. 

</TEXT>

