<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary on U.S. Trade Representative Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Article Sums Up Visit </H4>
<F P=102> OW0402101294 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0402101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article; "No Agreement Reached on Numerical </F>
Targets"] 
  [Text] U.S. Trade Representative Kantor visited Japan as 
an envoy of President Clinton to break a deadlock in Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks, but a series of meetings between him 
and Japanese Cabinet ministers ended 3 February, leaving the 
split in their opinions over numerical targets unbridged. Mr. 
Kantor left Japan for the United States on 4 February and it is 
believed he will report to President Clinton that the Japanese 
are determined to block the "numerical targets." Now, how the 
upcoming Japan-U.S. summit will settle the dispute over 
numerical targets has become a focal point. 
  During the series of meetings with Japanese ministers, Mr. 
Kantor stressed the importance of Japan-U.S. relations and then 
said: "If the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks fail to 
produce any results, the United States would adopt a different 
way." In this way, he suggested that the United States will not 
hesitate to restore the Super 301 provision of the 1988 Omnibus 
Trade Act. In response to his remarks, the Japanese side said: 
"He took a tough attitude in an attempt to press Japan for 
trade concessions" and added that this tough attitude was 
anticipated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

