<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bureaucrats React to Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502134894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Feb 93 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0502134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It was learned on 4 February that during a series 
of meetings with Japanese cabinet ministers, U.S. Trade 
Representative Kantor proposed that "Japanese and American 
politicians join delegations of the two countries to the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks." 
  In a bid to hammer out an accord in the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks prior to the Japan-U.S. summit slated for 11 
February, vice ministerial talks will be held in Washington 
beginning 7 February. The United States is still critical of 
Japanese bureaucrats, saying, "No progress can be expected 
because of tough Japanese bureaucrats." Mr. Kantor's proposal is 
believed aimed at extracting concessions from Japan on the issue 
of setting numerical targets which have become a focal point at 
the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks by having Japanese 
cabinet ministers attend the talks. In response, the Japanese 
Government rejected Mr. Kantor's proposal, saying, "We do not 
want to bring any change to the way the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks are held," (says a senior official in the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry). As a result, vice 
ministerial officials from the two countries will hold the talks. 
  Speaking at a news conference on 4 February, Mr. Kantor 
said, 
"Foreign Minister Hata will lead the Japanese effort and he will 
assume the responsibility for the talks." In this way, Mr. 
Kantor talked as if the Foreign Minister had promised him during 
a meeting that he would assume the responsibility for the talks. 
In response, Japanese bureaucrats reacted against Mr. Kantor's 
statement, saying, "Foreign Minister Hata did not make that 
promise," and confirmed anew that mainly working-level officials 
will attend the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

