<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa `Should' Visit U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502133194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0502133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] While the United States has demanded that Japan 
implement income tax reduction, the implementation has now been 
taken back to the drawing board amid the current confusion on 
the tax system reform. In this connection, a top Foreign 
Ministry [MOF] official stated on the evening of 4 February: 
"If the prime minister cancels the upcoming Japan-U.S. summit 
meeting because of a failure to implement tax cuts, it will be 
questioned how other issues would be dealt with." Thus, the 
official indicated that Prime Minister Hosokawa's visit to the 
United States set for 10 February should take place even if no 
conclusion is reached on the tax cuts issue. 

</TEXT>

