<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mori on Welfare Tax Plan, LDP Stance, Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402143494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0402143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of </F>
the Liberal Democratic Party, by unidentified NIHON KEIZAI 
SHIMBUN reporter on 3 February; place not given] 
  [Text] Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP], gave an interview to a NIHON KEIZAI 
SHIMBUN reporter on 3 February. Commenting on Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa's idea of introducing the national welfare 
tax, Mori stated: "The goal of the financial authorities is to 
increase the consumption tax. That counters our demand that 
income tax reductions be implemented to stimulate the slumping 
economy. The proposed rate of 7 percent for the welfare tax 
means the government will make clear gains after stop-gap 
national bonds are reimbursed." The LDP secretary general thus 
expressed his opposition to the idea of introducing a national 
welfare tax. Regarding the procedure for deciding on the new 
tax plan, Mori severely criticized the government stance, 
saying: "The problem is the government is being led by the 
Ministry of Finance. We see the weakness in deciding on the 
policies of the Hosokawa administration which fails to assert 
that the consumption tax should not be increased at the expense 
of implementing tax reductions." 
  On the LDP's future policies toward the Hosokawa 
administration, Mori said: "At the recent meeting with Prime 
Minister Hosokawa, Kono did not accept the prime minister's call 
for holding such meetings repeatedly." Thus he denied the 
possibility of taking a cooperative line with the coalition 
administration. At the same time, Mori said: "Boycotting the 
Diet sessions last time did not prove to our advantage, and we 
have lost trust in the LDP. Taking the stance of opposing all 
policies and fighting against them is inappropriate." Mori 
stressed that the LDP would take a free and unbiased stance 
depending on the policies, while maintaining a certain distance 
from the coalition administration for the time being. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

