<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 7 KYODO -- Leaders of Japan's 
governing coalition parties failed to agree on a key tax plan 
Monday [7 February], postponing the decision until Tuesday 
morning, sources said. Meeting throughout the day, the leaders 
of the seven parties remained divided on how to fund the tax 
cuts -- an issue that has threatened to split the coalition, the 
sources said. 
  They are to meet at 10:30 A.M. Tuesday to attempt once again 
to forge the tax plan, a central part of the government's 
planned economic stimulus plan, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

