<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOF To Assist Financial Institutions' Mergers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402054694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0512 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0402054694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 4 KYODO -- The Ministry of Finance [MOF] 
unveiled new administrative guidance Friday [4 February] to help 
mergers of financial institutions burdened with nonperforming 
loans. 
  Ministry officials said the guidance is designed to help 
banking and nonbanking firms liquidate bad loans as quickly as 
possible to promote economic recovery. 
  Financial institutions were urged to actively utilize 
Cooperative Credit Purchasing Co. to rid themselves of bad loans 
or high-risk loans, the officials said. 
  The company is a joint venture established by about 150 
commercial banks and finance firms to liquidate bad loans. 
  The ministry also urged financial institutions to consider 
transferring claims for which they have agreed to reduce or 
exempt interest payments to affiliates. 
  The guidance will be incorporated in a comprehensive package 
of pump-priming measures to be announced by the government in 
the near future, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

