<H3> <TI>   U.S. Companies Start Business After Embargo End </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0502113894 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 5 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0502113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Within hours of the lifting of the U.S. trade 
embargo, American companies started doing business in Vietnam. 
On Friday evening, some 200 Vietnamese and Americans met at a 
hotel in Hanoi to celebrate the event. An American credit 
company has signed a contract on the stipulation of credit cards 
in Vietnam and an American aviation company has announced plans 
to establish an air link from Los Angeles to Ho Chi Minh City. 
  Meanwhile, locally produced bottles of Pepsi Cola were 
hitting shop shelves in Ho Chi Minh City and Hanoi. Mr. [name 
indistinct], regional president of Pepsi Cola International, 
said at a press conference marking the event in Ho Chi Minh City 
on Friday: We have waited for this day for a long time. Pepsi 
is the first, and for now, the only [words indistinct] licensed 
to bottle its products in Vietnam. The company is producing an 
initial run of 1,500 cases for local sampling and will be fully 
operational in a week. 

</TEXT>

